transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Mr. King, how can I help you?

Speaker 2: Yes, hello, how are you?

Speaker 1: Hey, how are you doing? Am I speaking to Mr. King?

Speaker 2: Yes.

Speaker 1: Hey, Mr. King, how can I help you out today?

Speaker 2: Yes, today I was calling to make sure my prescription was canceled.

Speaker 1: Oh, wow. What's going on? Is it not working for you, or what's happening?

Speaker 2: Oh, it's nothing like that. I just can't afford it right now, so I wanted to halt all the...

Speaker 1: Oh, that's fine. You can order this when you want, sir.

Speaker 2: We can just stop everything, and you can order your next order in the next five months, whenever you want.

Speaker 1: Okay, that'll be no problem. I would just like to cancel it right now, and if I need to, I can call back and order.

Speaker 2: Yeah, so basically what we do is for the next five months, we'll just keep your prescription open and allow you to call for your refills on your own in that time.

Speaker 1: Okay, so I'll just go ahead and cancel it altogether, because I might forget, and then if I need it again...

Speaker 2: Yeah, but if you need it again, you won't have a prescription. That's why I'm trying to tell you we can keep it available.

Speaker 1: Okay, so is this five months, if I don't call back, then it'll start again?

Speaker 2: Well, you can get whatever you would want in five months. If you want to continue the same way that you are now, we can keep it that way.

Speaker 1: If you don't want it anymore, we can get rid of it. It's totally up to you, sir, on how you proceed.

Speaker 2: Yeah, that's okay. I'll just go ahead and cancel it.

Speaker 1: All right, just know you will not be able to reorder with us once your prescription is gone, okay?

Speaker 2: Okay, no problem.
